==Old English==
===Etymology===
From the Indo-European root ''*man-'' ‘hand’, which led to a Germanic base with a variety of meanings.  Cognates include Old Frisian ''mund'' ‘guardian, guardianship’, Old Saxon ''mund'' ‘hand’, Old High German [[munt]] ‘hand, protection’ (German [[Mund]], [[Munt]] ‘legal power of protection’), Old Icelandic ''mund'' ‘hand’, [[mundr]] ‘sum a bridgeroom pays his bride’.  The IE root was also the source of Latin [[manus]] ‘hand’, Albanian [[marr]] ‘turn’.

